        <td style="width:315px;">
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="VariableName-small" translate="true">Cross-Over</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> or is the point where the acceleration changes &apos;sign&apos; </text><image src="Red-14-1b.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Image Caption"></image><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">, or </text><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true">vice-versa</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#ff6600;" /></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="VariableName-small" translate="true">Cross-over Jerk</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> is the rate of change of acceleration [Jerk] at &apos;cross-over&apos; point It is important because this is where backlash is traversed. A </text><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline;" translate="true">low jerk</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> means the acceleration is not changing rapidly. When the acceleration is not changing rapidly and it the absolute acceleration is also near to zero, then the velocity is not changing rapidly. Thus the so-called backlash after impact also tends to be lower.</text></para>
        </td>
